{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488449","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488449"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:42:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/448"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.14,0.54,0.06,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97524"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44620"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97524"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three month history of a painless swelling in the right side of his scrotum. He has no other symptoms. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The swelling is 8 cm diameter and the testis cannot be felt as a distinct entity. The spermatic cord is well defined and can be felt clearly above the swelling.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Teratoma of the testis","Epididymal cyst","Hydrocele","Inguino-scrotal hernia","Varicocele"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classic case of a scrotal swelling where the key physical examination finding is that the spermatic cord can be felt as a separate structure above the swelling. This finding is crucial in differentiating between various scrotal pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen the examiner can get above the swelling and feel the spermatic cord clearly, this effectively rules out an \u003Cstrong\u003Einguino-scrotal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E. In a hernia, the swelling would extend up into the inguinal canal, making it impossible to get above the swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Evaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a collection of dilated veins in the pampiniform plexus that feels like a \u0027bag of worms\u0027 on examination. If present, it would involve the spermatic cord itself, making it unlikely that the cord would be palpable as a distinct, normal structure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are fluid-filled sacs that develop in the epididymis. They can typically be palpated as distinct entities alongside a normal testis. In this case, since the testis cannot be felt as a distinct entity, an epididymal cyst is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a collection of fluid between the layers of the tunica vaginalis surrounding the testis. This creates a smooth, fluctuant swelling that envelops the testis, making it difficult to palpate the testis separately from the swelling. The spermatic cord, however, remains normal and palpable above the swelling. This perfectly matches the description in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eteratoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the testis would present as a firm, irregular mass arising from the testis itself. Testicular tumors are most common in men aged 15-35 years, making this diagnosis less likely in a 65-year-old man. Additionally, the three-month history without other symptoms is atypical for a testicular malignancy, which would usually progress more rapidly or cause other symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most hydroceles in older men do not have any serious underlying cause"],"references":["Wampler S, Llanes M. Common Scrotal and Testicular Problems. Primary Care - Clinics in Office Practice, 2010;  37:613-626."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80120"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T15:22:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T15:24:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"448"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97524"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","